5. Security Deep Dive

Cryptographic Correctness

Algorithm	Implementation	Verdict	Notes	
Private Key Generation	`crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(32))`	✅ Correct	CSPRNG, 32 bytes, uniform distribution	
secp256k1 Public Key Derivation	`@noble/secp256k1.getPublicKey()`	✅ Correct	Uncompressed format (04 + x + y), 65 bytes	
Ethereum Address Hashing	`keccak256(pubkey[1:])` then last 20 bytes	✅ Correct	Standard keccak-256 on 64-byte uncompressed pubkey	
EIP-55 Checksum	Custom implementation in `crypto.js`	⚠️ Mostly Correct	Uses `TextEncoder().encode(addr)` on lowercase address. Standard is `keccak256(Buffer.from(addr, 'ascii'))`. TextEncoder produces UTF-8 which is identical for ASCII hex chars. Acceptable.	
Ed25519 (SOL/SUI/APT)	`@noble/ed25519`	✅ Correct	Proper library choice	
BIP-39 Entropy	`crypto.getRandomValues` → hex string	❌ BUGGY	See Critical Issues #1	
BIP-32 Derivation	`bip32.fromSeed` + `derivePath`	✅ Correct	Standard library	
AES-256-GCM Encryption	Web Crypto API	✅ Correct	100k PBKDF2 iterations, 16-byte salt, 12-byte IV	
Base58Check (Bitcoin)	Custom + `bs58`	✅ Correct	Double-SHA256 checksum, version byte 0x00	

Side-Channel & Timing Vulnerabilities

Vector	Risk	Mitigation Status	
Private key in memory	High — keys exist in JS heap, vulnerable to XSS/memory dump	No `SecureString` or `ArrayBuffer` zeroization on UI components	
Worker memory isolation	Medium — Workers have separate heaps but same process	Acceptable for client-side tool	
Timing attacks on pattern matching	Low — `matchesPattern` uses constant-time string comparison	✅ `slice()` + `===` is effectively constant-time for fixed-length compares	
Keystroke logging	Medium — seed phrase entry via keyboard	No virtual keyboard or input obfuscation	
Screen capture	Medium — private keys displayed in UI	Toggle show/hide exists, but no anti-screenshot overlays	

Key/Seed Export Handling

The export system has layered security:
- Keystore JSON — Password-encrypted, standard format-like
- QR Code — One-time with 5-minute TTL (though TTL is client-enforced, not cryptographic)
- Checksum verification — Pre-decryption integrity check

Weaknesses:
- `generateKeystoreJSON()` in `encryption.js` constructs a non-standard keystore (splits encrypted key by `$` delimiter). Not compatible with MetaMask/Geth import.
- No memory locking — decrypted keys remain in React state until component unmounts
- No `secure-context` requirement check — app may run over HTTP (though `crypto.subtle` requires HTTPS/localhost)

Poison Radar Effectiveness

The on-chain scanner is educational rather than forensic:
- Only analyzes 100 transactions max
- Known address list is hardcoded to 5 major tokens (USDT, USDC, WBTC, WETH, DAI) — trivial to bypass
- No contract code analysis, no token approval detection, no phishing signature detection
- Ethereum implementation only fetches `eth_getBalance`, not actual transaction history (the `fetchEthereumTxs` function is misnamed — it doesn't fetch transactions)
- Verdict: Useful as a teaching tool, but users should not rely on it for security decisions

